						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Related-developments/Deep-permeable-soils-buffer-impacts-of-crop-fertilizer-on-water-bodies" title="Deep, permeable soils buffer impacts of crop fertilizer on water bodies" alt="link">Deep, permeable soils buffer impacts of crop fertilizer on water bodies</a></h2>

	
					<p>Some of the damaging impacts of intensive agriculture on nearby streams, rivers, and their wildlife may be buffered by very deep and highly permeable soils. To somewhat mitigate the environmental impact of growing corn and soya, land with old, highly weathered, very deep soils that are uniform over great depths must be reserved.(via <a href="http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2013-04/mbl-dps042413.php" target="_blank">Eurekalert</a>, 24/04/2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">27/06/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Related-developments/Deep-permeable-soils-buffer-impacts-of-crop-fertilizer-on-water-bodies">Read more...</a>
